subSubSection.paragraph:
Remarks.

Chthonius ressli

does not closely resemble any of the Italian species of the 

C. ischnocheles

group, due its distinctive pattern of finger chelal teeth. The only species with a similar dentition pattern is 

C. hungaricus
Mahnert, 1981

from 
Hungary
, 
Romania
and 
Slovakia
(
Mahnert 1981
; 
Christophoryová, Fenďa & Krištofík 2011
; 
Gardini 2014
). 

Chthonius ressli

differs from 

C. hungaricus

in the following main characters: anterior eyes usually reduced and posterior eyes as vestigial remains (anterior eyes with convex lens and posterior eyes with flat lens in 

C. hungaricus

); anterior margin of carapace without preocular microsetae (with 1 microseta on each side in 

C. hungaricus

); posterior margin of carapace with 4 macrosetae (with 2 macrosetae in 

C. hungaricus

); chelicerae without lateral microsetae (with 1 lateral microseta in 

C. hungaricus

); chela length 0.45–0.535 (
♂
) or 0.53–0.62 (
♀
) mm [0.65–0.66 (
♂
) or 0.71–0.73 (
♀
) mm in 

C. hungaricus

]; movable chelal finger length 0.30–0.36 (
♂
) or 0.34–0.41 (
♀
) mm [0.44–0.47 (
♂
), 0.48–0.49 (
♀
) mm in 

C. hungaricus

].
